A GAMLSS re-analysis of an RT data set (with a focus on dataâ€™s shape)

Fernando Marmolejo-Ramos

20 abril, 2022

Introduction

The following features GAMLSS techniques to model a data set. The data set will be from a study by Moret-Tatay 1. A short tutorial on GAMLSS can be found in Stasinopoulos et al.Â (2018) 2.

The plan is to showcase GAMLSS techniques to model the dataâ€™s shape; i.e.Â skewness and kurtosis. A paper that describes this approach can be found in de Bastiani et al.Â (in press) 3.

Uploading the data

# data can be easily uploaded via the 'import dataset' tab in R studio...
library(readxl)
data <- read_excel(file.choose())


# retaining correct RTs that are between 250 and 1800 milliseconds
data2 <- subset(data, RT<1800 & RT>250 & Accuracy==1)

# ensuring all variables of interest are well
data2$Participant <- as.factor(data2$Participant)
data2$Group <- as.factor(data2$Group)
data2$Condition <- as.factor(data2$Condition)

Modelling the shape of the model

First some GAMLSS models are created. The models will consider all the distributionâ€™s parameters. Specifically the Normal (N) and ExGaussian (EG) distributions are considered.

library(gamlss)
# model
mu<-as.formula(RT ~ Group * Condition + random(Participant))
sigma<-mu
nu<-mu


# two-parameters normal model

N <- gamlss(mu, 
            sigma.formula = sigma,
               family = NO,
               data=data2)

Letâ€™s examine the modelsâ€™s AIC values and look at the residuals.

# N and EG fits
list(normal_fit = N$aic, EG_fit = EG$aic)
## $normal_fit
## [1] 55985.14
## 
## $EG_fit
## [1] 55018.92
# residuals

plot(N)

The EG model gives a better fit as shown by the AIC and the residual plots. Ideally, residuals should have a mean of 0, variance = 1, skewness = 0, and kurtosis = 3.

The results indicate the four-parameters Box-Cox power exponential distribution gives the best fit. Letâ€™s check the residuals:

# four-parameters Box-Cox power exponential
tau <- mu

BCPE <- gamlss(mu, 
            sigma.formula = sigma,
            nu.formula = nu,
            tau.formula = tau,
               family = BCPE,
               data=data2)
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 1: Global Deviance = 55001.69

Buckeplots

Buckeplots with existing data (an example)

First off, letâ€™s illustrate these plots with existing data. In this example, only the location parameter is modelled and a P-spline is used on one of the numeric covariates.

library(gamlss.ggplots)

bccg <- gamlss(R~pb(Fl)+A+B, data=rent, family=BCCG)
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 1: Global Deviance = 28024.31 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 2: Global Deviance = 27962.92 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 3: Global Deviance = 27960.95 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 4: Global Deviance = 27960.78 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 5: Global Deviance = 27960.76 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 6: Global Deviance = 27960.75 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 7: Global Deviance = 27960.75 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 8: Global Deviance = 27960.75
no <- gamlss(R~pb(Fl)+A+B, data=rent, family=NO)
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 1: Global Deviance = 28326.39 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 2: Global Deviance = 28326.39
moment_bucket(bccg, no, no_bootstrap = 100)

# by a categorical covariate
moment_bucket_wrap(bccg, no, no_bootstrap = 100, xvar=rent$B) 

moment_bucket_wrap(bccg, no, no_bootstrap = 100, 
                   col_bootstrap = c('peru','red'),
                   colour_bucket = T,
                   # col_JB_test = 'pink',
                   xvar=rent$Fl)

Another function for bucketplots

# function 'bp' in the gamlss package does the job
# but note the 'overlap' argument seems not to be working! (see rent$Fl)
# note this argument applies to numeric covariates

# thus a function sent by Fernanda de Bastiani is used here
source("bp.R")

bp.fernanda(list(bccg,no), xvar=~rent$Fl*rent$B, 
   show.legend = T,
   overlap = 0)

To fix the error in the argument overlap and generate more intuitive labels for the rows and columns, try the following

`Floor space (sqr mtr)` <-cut(rent$Fl, 4) 
# 4 cuts of equal length are requested 
#note this doesn't entail equal number of observations in each level

`Bathroom (0=no, 1=yes)` <- rent$B

bp.fernanda(list(bccg,no), 
   xvar=~`Floor space (sqr mtr)`*`Bathroom (0=no, 1=yes)`, 
   show.legend = T,no.bootstrap = 99,
   overlap = 0)

Buckeplots for current data

# to give nicer looking labels for the rows and columns
Group <- data2$Group
Condition <- data2$Condition

# N=normal distribution, E=EG distribution, B=BCPE distribution

bp.fernanda(list(N,EG, BCPE), xvar=~Group*Condition, 
   show.legend = T, no.bootstrap = 99,
   text.to.show = c('N','E','B'),
   overlap = 0)
